        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The correlator would be set up in the spectral line mode with the representaive spectral window occupying one of the basebands covering the CO 1-0 line, with averaging of 4 to obtain a resolution of ~5 km/s, far smaller than the expected line width. The other three basebands will be set in the continuum mode to detect any continuum emission from the target galaxy, and at the very least enabling better continuum subtraction through higher sensitivity imaging the field of view.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to detect the total CO 1-0 line flux over the target galaxy, and therefore request for the most compact 12 m configuration, for which the coarsest allowed angular resolution is 6 arcseconds. We estimate that even with this resolution three synthesized beams would be required to cover the extent of the CO emission from the target galaxy. 
The major optical diameter of the galaxy is 20 arcseconds and we do not expect the CO emission to extend beyond this scale. 20 arcseconds is below the maximum recoverable scale without ACA, and therefore we do not need 7m or TP observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We intend to observe the CO J 1-0 line from the target galaxy UM 461. The galaxy has a heliocentric velocity of ~892 km/s, which means the line is observable with the ALMA Band-3 receiver. The expected total gas mass is estimated from the measured dust mass of the galaxy (Remy-Ruyer et al. 2013), by multiplying it with a gas-to-dust mass ratio estimated using the fit from Remy-Ruyer et al. (2014) for metallicities below 12+log(O/H)&lt;8.1. After subtraction the atomic gas mass from the total gas mass (Madden et al. 2013, van Zee et al. 1998), we are left with the estimated molecular gas mass. Next to get the estimated CO flux density integrated over the line, we divide the estimated molecular gas mass by an alpha_CO value extrapolated from the empirical calibration of alpha_CO with metallicity derived by Leroy et al. (2011). We conservatively estimate the CO 1-0 line width to be equal to the HI FWHM of 71 km/s (Smoker et al. 2000). Assuming that the extent of the expected CO emission would be the same as the PACS 70 micron dust emission (spatial resolution same as what we intend to use here), we find that three 6 arcsecond beams will be enough to cover the extent of the emission. From the estimated value of CO flux density integrated over the line, we arrive at an estimated peak CO flux density of 2.07 mJy per synthesised beam over the line FWHM. We aim to detect the expected line flux density at 5 sigma significance at a velocity resolution matched to the line FWHM, i.e. 71 km/s. This implies an rms noise on 0.395 mJy per 71 km/s.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
