    <prp:abstract>We propose to use ALMA Band-3 to observe the CO J 1-0 line from a nearby 17% solar metallicity galaxy, for a pilot study to test a startegy of accurately determining the H_2 mass of, and the CO-to-H_2 conversion factor for very low metallicity (&lt; 20% solar) dwarfs. The strategy involves using two independent determinations of the H_2 content of the galaxy as additional constraints. The first comes from a newly developed method based on radiative transfer simulations, which uses the [CII] 158 micron line flux to trace the mass of H_2 for very low metallicity dwarfs. The second constraint on the H_2 content is obtained using the traditional method of estimating gas mass from the dust mass, which we plan to refine using an accurate estimation of the gas-to-dust ratio based on recent models of dust evolution in late type dwarfs. The proposed pilot observations and the results obtained from it using our newly developed startegy will be used as a template for determining the molecular hydrogen content of  dwarf galaxies with metallicity &lt; 20% the solar value with the full ALMA, and at the same time precisely calibrate the CO-to-H_2 conversion factor for very low metallicities.</prp:abstract>
